From e87503e343e44a3a2779afda3c1ac6898bee8a0b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Vester Imanuel Thacker <vic@pgsdf.org>
Date: Sat, 11 Jul 2026 03:42:41 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] pgsd-loader: add f7probe, a one-shot Go/Charm F7 diagnostic

The gdb-transfer.sh modes drove gdb through a grep-filtered pipe, and
that filtering repeatedly hid the very diagnostic each mode was meant
to surface: a missing continue made a sample loop read a halted CPU,
a bare commands block bound only to the last breakpoint so landmark
prints never fired, and breakpoints that may not resolve to the
running kernel left no visible error. Each defect cost a bench
round-trip to find.

f7probe replaces that with a single tool that captures everything.
It builds the loader, stages the transfer-armed real-kernel ESP,
discovers the trampoline address from the loader NVRAM breadcrumb,
runs QEMU halted under a gdb stub, drives gdb through the transfer
and the early-kernel landmarks (amd64_loadaddr, hammer_time,
native_parse_preload_data, getmemsize, init_param1, cninit) with a
command block bound per breakpoint by number, and writes the full
unfiltered gdb and serial transcripts to /tmp. It then prints a
structured report (Transfer, Kernel bring-up checklist, a reasoned
Verdict, Evidence) rendered with Charm's lipgloss.

Verified end to end in emulation against the contract fake: the
report shows the cr3 switch, entry reached, no FreeBSD landmark hit
(the fake has no such symbols), and the HOK serial, with markers and
serial tail sanitized to valid UTF-8. On the real kernel the tool
will show which landmarks resolve and where boot stops, with the raw
gdb transcript preserved so breakpoint-resolution errors are visible
rather than filtered away.

Dependencies are pinned in go.mod/go.sum and not vendored (offline
build verified from the module cache with GOPROXY=off), consistent
with keeping large blobs out of the tree; the binary and any vendor
dir are gitignored.

Bench: cd pgsd-loader/tools/f7probe && go build -o f7probe . then
PGSD_REAL_KERNEL=/boot/kernel/kernel ./f7probe
